At the time of its closest approach on January 26, the asteroid will be approximately 745,000 miles (1.2 million kilometers) from Earth. 

Due to its orbit around the sun, the asteroid is currently only visible by astronomers with large telescopes who are located in the southern hemisphere. 

But by Jan. 26, the space rock's changing position will make it visible to those in the northern hemisphere. 

From its reflected brightness, astronomers estimate that the asteroid is about a third of a mile (0.5 kilometers) in size. 

